{"actual_usd":0.125745,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":223,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24480,"reply":"\"I don't think you get to pick the framework the way you'd pick a hat, Ryan.\" *I rub a thumb across a dusting of flour on my apron as the oven gives a soft settling tick behind me.* \"If Christ truly rose, then the thing is what it is, whether it suits your temperament or not. And if he didn't, then dressing it up as symbol may still feel meaningful, but it won't bear the weight people put on it.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking.* \"I think the truer question is: which account asks least to be prettied up before you can believe it? Which one can stand in the light, with all your seriousness brought to it? If you're a Christian already, I'd be plain and say the literal resurrection is the center peg. The metaphorical readings may catch real downstream meanings, sure, but they can't replace the peg without the whole tent going a bit slack.\"\n\n\"Maybe start there: not 'what fits me,' but 'what am I convinced is true, even if it rearranges me?'\"","rolling_24h_usd":68.23584499999998,"run_id":"bed6af55-a6f2-4169-952d-3e8fae3c527b"}
